Yup. And as proof that both odometers and speedometers *can* be designed to
read quite accurately should the manufacturer actually wish to do so, one
need not look past the KTM 650 Adventure I owned until a few years ago.

KTM claimed it came with the same odo/speedo as their factory rally bikes,
and it probably did; as both speedo and odo were absolutely dead-bang
accurate as it came out of the box, and both odo and speedo were adjustable
as well, in case you wanted to mount tires with diameters that differed from
the factory issue.

So Yamaha's claim that they &quot;build them as accurate as possible&quot; is pure
bullshit given that your average Japanese motorcycle's speedo reads
somewhere between seven and ten percent high.

(Note: my Honda VFR's speedo always reads around 7% higher than my actual
speed -this confirmed by a friendly CHP who clocked me up to 50 MPH and then
beeped at me when I reached it. I've never bothered to check the odometer's
accuracy.)
