Huh? As a tire wears and becomes smaller in diameter, it does not rotate
faster if you ride at the same speed as indicated by the speedometer. Your
actual speed decreases due to the reduced diameter. I have compared my
speedometer to a GPS for a while now and it becomes more optimistic as the
tire wears. Replacing the tire makes the speedometer more accurate for a
while. This might be more noticeable on a motorcycle, like my 919, that has
the speedometer sensor on the countershaft. Rear tires wear fairly fast on
this bike. At the same time, the odometer seems very accurate so why can't
they calibrate the speedometer a little closer? My speedometer reads about
9% high and so do our other two Hondas and so did my Hinckley Triumph.
Several people I know have newer Harleys and they have accurate
speedometers.
