is optimistic. After futzing with the Sigma for a few days
after I got it, I realized that bikes had some built in
inaccuracies for any device based on wheel rotations.

I like the Sigma both for reasonably the accurate speed
readings and also because it's nice to have the other
features such as clock and second trip odometer.

I may eventually break down and buy a GPS, but haven't
gotten there yet.

The popular BMW explanation for an optimistic speedo is
that they're required by local law to have a non-pessimistic
speed reading and err on the side of optimism. (So you
don't accidentally exceed speed limits ?)
